<font color="#FF0000">THE SORROW OF WAR</font><br>
<tt>Sat Jan  3 17:31:05 US/Eastern 1998
</tt><p>
P.S.<br>
Bao Ninh's &quot;The Sorrow of War,&quot; as mentioned in the Times article is a fictional account of an NVA's soldiers struggle with the pains of war, however, I highly recommand it. Bao reflects well on what the warrior suffers and endures in war, at times you forget its a former enemy's account, that you're reading because he echos much of what we have shared in different threads on this site.<br><br>
&quot;In the past months of the wet season Kien had been posted to the MIA team charged with gathering the remains of the dead from the worst battlefields. He had crossed almost all of the northern sector of the Central Highlands, returning to the sites of innumerable battles.<br>
The MIA team had uncovered a vast family of forgotten members of their regiment, dead under the mantle of the warm jungle. <br>
The fallen soldiers shared one destiny; no longer were there honrable or disgraced soldiers, heroic or cowardly, worthly or worthless. Now they were merely names and remains.<br>
For some of the other dead, not even that. Some had been totally vaporized, or blasted into such small pieces that their remains had long since been liquidized into mud.<br>
After some final touches with the shovel their graves would be done, their remains laid out. Then with their final breath their sould released, flying upwards, free. <br>
The uprush of so many souls penetrated Kien's mind, ate into his consciousness, becoming a dark shadow overhanging his own soul. Over a long period, over many, many graves, the souls of the beloved dead silently and gloomily dragged the sorrow of war into his life.&quot;<br><br>
From &quot;Sorrow of War,&quot; Bao Ninh, Riverhead Books, 1993 (c) <br>
Available through Barnes &amp; Noble, Dalton book stores.<br><br>
Cook
